Over the last few weeks I‚Äôve been trying to get my health and fitness back on track. Like many others, the weeks and months leading up to the holidays brought extra indulgences. A lot of them. And for me, most were due to sheer laziness. I was ordering in instead of cooking for myself, overeating instead of listening to my body, unable/unwilling to hold back when I wanted a treat, and I wasn‚Äôt working out. And there it was... that extra 5-10 (or 12) pounds. Nothing major to most, but for me, it left me feeling disappointed that I‚Äôd seemingly forgotten how take care of myself.
.
I keep seeing things about body positivity and acceptance, celebrating the extra curves that make you YOU, etc. And yassss I love it and I‚Äôm all for it! It‚Äôs such an important movement and a huge step from toxic pressures created by the media. But for me... the additional lbs, a wrecked gut and a loss of muscle tone aren‚Äôt things I want to accept. I won‚Äôt celebrate being too tired/lazy to go grocery shopping and cook for myself, and I won‚Äôt celebrate the fact that I haven‚Äôt worked out consistently in over two years. So, I‚Äôm giving myself permission to be disappointed in myself and I‚Äôm using that energy not for punishment, but as fuel for motivation to get back on track. Because there is a HUGE difference in eating healthy to nourish your body and eating healthy because you‚Äôre trying to punish yourself. And there‚Äôs a HUGE difference between working out because you have the privilege of being able to exercise your body, and working out because you‚Äôre trying to beat yourself up.
.
I don‚Äôt care what number the scale says.... but I do care how I feel on the inside and about my overall health and well-being. To me, taking care of oneself is the ultimate form of self-love and I haven‚Äôt been loving myself to the best of my ability lately. So yes, let‚Äôs love and accept the bodies we‚Äôve been given, but let‚Äôs remember to love them by taking good care of them - whatever that looks like for you. üí™üèº

This spot just felt so peaceful to me. And as I put my camera away, it was in that moment that I knew I‚Äôd be back. Next time with a permit to camp.

Back in 2009 I posted a photo to Facebook from a solo hike I‚Äôd done. I had set my point and shoot camera up on a rock, set the timer and ran in front of it. And one of my cousins commented on the photo and said something like ‚Äúthis looks like it belongs in an Athleta catalog!‚Äù ...those were kind words for the quality of the shot, but it sparked something. Hiking was still pretty new to me, but that comment made me wish I could be an active/outdoor model. So I figured I should get some modeling experience. ...right? ü§∑üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
.
I created a profile on a website that connects models with photographers and wow... I felt suuuuuuper out of my element. But I bit the bullet and began reaching out to see if somebody (anybody) wanted to take my photo. And pretty soon, I was meeting strangers and doing shoots just for the fun of it. But not the kind of photos you see here. Studio work, portraits, editorial, lingerie, lifestyle, etc... nothing relating to the outdoors and hiking. Some shoots were fun, some were weird, some were uncomfortable... but out of all of that, I made two really good friends that are still in my life today, and I have some great, as well as some super laughable photos of myself.
.
I remember the first time I‚Äôd heard about Instagram. I was shooting with @jordanvoth and he took a bts shot and posted to it. It wasn‚Äôt too much longer that I created an account for myself. My page was a smattering of random things; my new shoes, the fancy looking mojito my dad made me, a birthday dinner, a photo from a hike and every once in a while... one of those ‚Äúmodeling‚Äù shots. But then I decided to dedicate my Instagram feed to hiking photos only, and Missholldoll happened. ...and my account began to grow, and grew some more... and some more.
.
About a week ago it dawned on me that I did a job with @Athleta last month. Wait. What? ...and I laughed as I realized the sequence of events that lead me there. My cousins comment on a pretty average photo sparked something that snowballed into THIS. How freaking cool is that??
.
So thank you. Thank you to my cousin, thank you @jordanvoth, thank you @falcofoto, thank you @jayboyzee and thank YOU (yes you) for being here. üíï

node.text:
‚ÄúI‚Äôd rather find the right guy in 5 or 10 years, than the wrong guy tomorrow.‚Äù I was recently asked a series of interview questions for @likeamountaingirl (which isn‚Äôt available just yet) and one of which asked if I had a phrase or motto that I live by and what that means to me.
.
I haven‚Äôt been in a relationship for 8 years. My last relationship ended two months before I turned 30 and it took me a while to heal enough to begin attempting to move forward. And moving forward meant starting to date again. I reactivated old online dating profiles, downloaded apps and spent so much time swiping, scrolling, messaging, meeting for drinks, etc., and I just felt so empty. I didn‚Äôt like the fact that I was literally shopping for a relationship, again. Essentially interviewing men for a job and trying to fill the position. So even though my previous relationship came by way of online dating, I realized I no longer wanted to meet someone that way.
.
So I stopped. I closed it all down and I made a decision to let go of trying to find a boyfriend/future husband. I let go of feeling like I HAD to have children and I freed myself of any timeline - which made things like online dating and ‚Äúputting myself out there‚Äù kind of irrelevant. I realized that I would rather wait for the right person at the right time, than potentially force something in order to achieve the goals of marriage and a family. Those were the goals I grew up thinking I had to reach, because society tells us that‚Äôs just what you do! But it doesn‚Äôt have to be.
.
So here I am. Almost 38. It‚Äôs been 9 years since I‚Äôve brought someone home to meet my family. I‚Äôm single not because there is something wrong with me... but because I choose to wait for love to find me in its own way, in its own time. I get teased from time to time and I can equally make light of it. It‚Äôs not that being single isn‚Äôt ‚Äúnormal,‚Äù seemingly it‚Äôs that I‚Äôm not actively looking to remedy the situation that is so strange to many. But that‚Äôs because I don‚Äôt view being single as a negative thing. I used to, but not anymore. Instead I find it incredibly empowering.

Somehow this local spot has become a favorite of mine. It didn‚Äôt use to be, in fact, I used to hate it. I would hike it about once a year, and swear I‚Äôd never do it again.
.
It‚Äôs an incredibly busy trail. One that‚Äôs close to the city, and short enough in length to welcome all to enjoy it. I used to find garbage at the top, encounter groups of people playing music loudly, cutting switchbacks, and just overall practicing poor trail etiquette. It was never the experience I was wanted... but the year round access kept inviting me back.
.
And then, I broke my ankle on it. On an ‚Äúeasy‚Äù trail that I despised. I still laugh that of all the places I go, THAT‚Äôs where I broke it. But wow... thank goodness. Because when you go on a sunset solo hike in the winter, and you break your ankle.... being on an accessible trail not too far from civilization is such a blessing.
.
Once I was able to walk well enough to hike, this was the first place I came. And then I came back again, and again and again. And I see it differently now. I see it‚Äôs beauty. I see a trail available for any and everyone of varying skill levels. I see it‚Äôs dangers and know now to never be fooled by something I deem ‚Äúeasy.‚Äù
.
Photo: @jayboyzee

#Sponsored When the seasons change, so does my skin. Cold temps, wind, dry air with lower humidity levels are all contributors to my winter skin, which can be dry, scaly, itchy and just overall uncomfortable. So here are a few simple #skinrelief tips to help get us all through winter!
.
-Moisturize! The new @AveenoUS Cracked Skin Relief Cica Collection is made with Triple Oat Complex and comes in both an ointment and a balm. I keep the ointment with me when I‚Äôm out and about and use the balm at home.
.
-Hydrate! Drink that water guys and try to avoid an overload of caffeinated beverages that will dehydrate you. I tend to want more hot drinks this time of year, which usually equates to more coffee. Swapping that second or third cup of coffee with herbal tea or hot lemon water can be really helpful.
.
-Get a humidifier! I‚Äôm definitely indoors a lot more this time of year and switching between indoor heating and the cold temps outside can be harsh on the skin. A humidifier will help to replace that lost moisture!
.
-Avoid long hot showers/baths (which can strip your skin of its protective oils)! Keep them short and sweet, pat dry and MOISTURIZE while your skin is still damp. I love the @AveenoUS Cracked Skin Relief Cica Balm - it helps to seal in moisture and protect my skin. .
Winter is coming... and so is winter skin - be good to it!

My home state. üíï I was born and raised in this beautiful place... but I‚Äôm embarrassed as to how long it took me to truly appreciate it.
.
I didn‚Äôt start hiking until I was about 26 years old, and it wasn‚Äôt until then that my eyes were opened to the beauty all around me. Sure the mountains were beautiful, but that‚Äôs obvious. It was finding beauty in the the tiny details and intricacies of nature that surprised me the most.

I didn‚Äôt know what hike I was going to do until about ten minutes before I reached the mountain pass. I was still hemming and hawing for most of the drive. I didn‚Äôt know how far I would go, I didn‚Äôt know how long I would stay and I didn‚Äôt expect to take a little side trail to this pretty view on the way back to the car.
.
The beauty of solo hiking. The decisions are yours and yours alone. #mymountaintherapy
.
Note: It‚Äôs always important to let someone know where you‚Äôre heading when going hiking - especially when you are by yourself. I was able to get a couple texts off to my sister and a friend letting them know where I was heading once I made my decision and before I lost service. Be safe out there!

Believe it or not, I often struggle with feeling like I‚Äôm not outdoorsy enough, like I don‚Äôt travel enough or like I‚Äôm just not getting after it as much as I should... and I apologize if I contribute to that mindset for any of you.
.
I don‚Äôt think I hit the trails any more or less than I have in previous years, but as I scroll through the feed on Instagram and watch others stories, it‚Äôs there... and it‚Äôs cumulative. I‚Äôm heading to work, while others are setting off on yet another trip, another hike, another sunset or sunrise.
.
I constantly have to remind myself of the choice I have made; a choice I continue to make every single day. To go into an office building, to sit at a desk and to collect a consistent and reliable paycheck. It‚Äôs something I‚Äôm grateful for, but also feel resentful of at times - as I‚Äôm sure many of you can relate.
.
This post is a reminder to not compare apples to oranges. I don‚Äôt necessarily like the phrase ‚Äúhighlight reel‚Äù as for me, what you see in my feed isn‚Äôt that. Sure, it‚Äôs photogenic, but these aren‚Äôt my best moments. My highlights are the ones you‚Äôll mostly likely never see. They are the moments that challenge me, scare me, bring tears to my eyes, make me laugh until I almost pee myself, and of course, those that are filled with love. A camera set up on a tripod while a timer counts down, will never capture that.
.
So while I scroll through my feed, question my choices or find myself feeling envious of others... I remind myself that I have so much to be thankful for, and that social media is not a very accurate representation of real life. Not for me anyway. And also, a reminder that we all have a choice in what we see and experience on here. If social media creates negative feelings for you, you can look at it less, mute and unfollow people and of course delete it altogether. The choice is ours.

I‚Äôm beginning to feel a little better, I think. Some of that is just admitting and embracing that my Seasonal Depression has arrived, but also, it‚Äôs taking control of the situation to the best of my ability.
.
Here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve done the last two days: I‚Äôm waking up to a lightly lit room and birds chirping thanks to my sunrise alarm. I drink water and get the coffee pot going. I do 5-10 minutes on my climbing machine to just get my body moving and help wake me up. Then I hop in the shower (yesterday was just a quick rinse, but this morning I had to wash my mane üíÜüèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è). After that, I pour a cup of coffee, sit down and turn my Happy ‚Äútherapy‚Äù light on for 15 minutes. Then I‚Äôm ready to finish getting ready work and head on out! Breakfast right now is just some oatmeal with walnuts and a banana which I have when I get to work, and that‚Äôs also when I take my vitamins.
.
So ya.... feeling a bit better, but I think it will take a little longer to begin to feel really like myself again. Just gotta keep at it and push through! I hope these posts help some of my fellow Seasonal Affective Disorder friends out there. We‚Äôre in this together!
.
Photo by: @disa for @glyder

node.text:
October is probably my least favorite month. Which is a bummer, because I actually DO like the transition into fall. The colors, the pumpkins, clothing layers, the crisp air.. all the things. But what I don‚Äôt love, is getting hit with Seasonal Affective Disorder like a ton of bricks.
.
It‚Äôs something I used to pay no mind to and assumed it was just people who just didn‚Äôt like the weather, or the cold, or who would get stir crazy because they were indoors more... but it‚Äôs not. I mean, sure, I love summer, but I‚Äôm not unhappy that it‚Äôs fall. I truly enjoy the varying seasons and what each one has to offer. But I know I FEEL the best during the spring and summer months.
.
Things I‚Äôve learned about SAD (seasonal affective disorder):
-it doesn‚Äôt affect everyone.
-women are four times more likely to get it.
-scientists/medical professionals still don‚Äôt fully understand what causes it, but it‚Äôs believed that the lack of daylight plays a big part in naturally occurring vitamin D and serotonin levels.
-some of the symptoms are: constant fatigue, lack of focus, poor sleep, muscle and joint pain, withdrawal from life/social activities, anxiety, overall deflated and disheartened feelings, irritability and some eating and weight problems.
.
For me, it feels like a dull headache and a grogginess that will not go away, along with low energy. Kinda like I‚Äôm hungover actually... that‚Äôs probably the best way to describe it, although I feel like most of the above symptoms do apply in some way or another. I believe I can pinpoint when it starts happening, and it‚Äôs usually when we begin getting less than 12 hours of daylight. Right now Seattle is getting less than 11, so it‚Äôs pretty noticeable.
.
So that‚Äôs where I‚Äôm at, and it kinda sucks... but I‚Äôve dug out my sunrise alarm clock & therapy light, I‚Äôm going to take vitamins and focus on a healthy diet and daily exercise, and of course... when I get can step outside and grab some lunch during the work week, I do. Hopefully I‚Äôll get back on track soon, because between this and fighting off a cold - I‚Äôve missed out on some incredible fall weather here in Washington.
.
What about you? Do you suffer from SAD? #seasonaldepression

This is me. Smiley, happy, 37 year old me. My life isn‚Äôt what I thought it would be at this age. Single, never married and no children. I‚Äôm sure if you‚Äôd told early-to-mid-20‚Äôs Holly all of this, she would have been DEVASTATED. Because back then that was how I measured life success.
.
But to 37 year old Holly, life success has come in the form of close meaningful relationships, a job I enjoy - where I‚Äôm surrounded by some really great people, a cat-child that always makes me laugh and feel loved... and for me, it also comes in the form of having access to the outdoors and choosing to be a part of it.
.
But more than that, life success has been becoming more and more comfortable in my own skin... it‚Äôs come from letting go of the need to appease everyone and feeling obligated to maintain relationships that don‚Äôt bring me joy.... and it‚Äôs come from making the choice to veer away from some of those societal norms that I kept trying to force myself into.
.
My life often feels messy and sometimes stagnant, but it‚Äôs my very own beautiful creation and it‚Äôs always evolving - even if I can‚Äôt see it. The only version of life success that I strive for is... do things that make me happy and surround myself with people (and pets!) where love and acceptance are reciprocal. As long I‚Äôm still focusing on that 10, 20, 50+ years from now, l know I‚Äôll feel proud of what I‚Äôve accomplished.
.
Photo by: @disa for @glyder üíï

To elaborate a little more off of last nights post (and if you missed it, go there and come back!) ...the decision to just start doing something on my own and by myself was huge in itself. I was a relatively insecure person for many of my younger years. So that alone was a big and important step for me.
.
The time spent outdoors was and still is incredibly therapeutic, and even to this day, when I feel stressed, I turn to the mountains. Hiking allowed me to heal and grow mentally and emotionally, as well as providing physical exercise and wellness. I started to feel fit, strong and confident, and it began to spread to other areas of my life. I can even say that hiking has indirectly had an impact on how I approach companionship - a topic I have yet to really cover here, but have been thinking more on lately...
.
The decisions we‚Äôve made in life (whether big or small) have lead us to where we are now. Heck, even the decision to open up this silly app lead you right here. For me (and I‚Äôm sure many of you), it‚Äôs just very interesting to wonder where I‚Äôd be and what I‚Äôd be doing if I‚Äôd never taken that leap and discovered my passion for the outdoors.
.

.
When the final days before winter conditions collide with the turning of the golden larches you get what‚Äôs known as... Larch Madness! I‚Äôm glad I did it, and we eventually lost the crowds as we veered off towards a less popular destination... but next year I‚Äôll be looking for something a bit more off the beaten path. node.text:
Hey you! Hi there! üëãüèº How are you?
.
In all seriousness, I‚Äôd love for you to tell me a little something about yourself. Whether you engage with me regularly or never have before, tell me something NOW. It can be long or short. Detailed or vague. Serious or comical. Tell me what you had for lunch. Or what your favorite thing to do on a Saturday is. Anything. You can even just say ‚Äúhi.‚Äù
.
I often find myself longing for the days where my social media account felt like it used to... like a warm and welcoming community of users all finding a common place to connect. And sometimes I still feel that, but more often than not, I don‚Äôt. And now, our accounts are flooded with fake users, accounts with mass followings who are only trying to get you to follow them back, generic bot-like comments, etc. I could go on...
.
I just know I would always rather have quality over quantity, and real versus fake. So I‚Äôm currently in the process of trying to find a service to help remove/block accounts that aren‚Äôt here to engage WITH me. So wish me luck with that, and in the meantime, I‚Äôd love for YOU to engage with me. So please, tell me something about yourself.
.
Ok I‚Äôll start...
.
I have a grumpy cat sauna hat. Yep. You read that right. I wear a hat with grumpy cat on it in a co-ed public sauna... paired with some kind of swimwear of course. And I look... AWESOME. üòπ And if I get enough requests, maybe I‚Äôll post a photo with it to my story. Anyway, I look forward to reading your comments! Thanks guys!! üôèüèº

I hiked in a constant cloud yesterday (not pictured). Zero mountain views made for a sad Holly + the mist from said cloud totally ruined my hair. üòÇ But, I still saw a bunch of rocks and huckleberry bushes. Or blueberry bushes. I‚Äôm actually not super sure I can tell a difference. Anyway, now I‚Äôm in the office... under fluorescent lights. Meanwhile it‚Äôs sunny AF outside. üòê #happymonday

We stopped at a ranger station to acquire a backcountry permit and were reminded to camp only on dirt and rocks, absolutely NO foliage. When we arrived, we scoured the area and found just one obvious campsite. All dirt, lined with rocks. But even then, we dropped our packs and continued to roam around in search for additional options. We brought the required bear canister and blue bags for human waste. We did all the things, and yet... I haven‚Äôt wanted to post this image because I‚Äôm confident the first thing that will come to some folks minds is ‚Äúthat‚Äôs not 200 feet from the water!‚Äù And that wouldn‚Äôt be an inaccurate statement - I‚Äôm pretty sure it wasn‚Äôt. It‚Äôs definitely farther from the water than this image makes it appear... but that‚Äôs the fun and sometimes difficult part about photography.
.
LNT are guidelines that all of us wilderness lovers should know and practice. But the stars don‚Äôt always align where you can check all the boxes. So do the best you can. Good campsites are found, not made. Clearing out an area, farther from the water would have done far more damage to this fragile place than taking up residency in an already existing spot closer to the lake.
.
But the point of this post is... there‚Äôs a lot of flack these days, people and accounts being reported and blasted for outdoor ethics or lack thereof. I‚Äôm in full support of respecting and protecting the environment, following the rules, and putting those things above myself and my images... but it‚Äôs good to remember this; a simple image doesn‚Äôt usually tell a complete story.

Moisture is the essence of wetness, and wetness is the essence of beauty. - Derek Zoolander üí¶üßúüèº‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è
.

node.text: I love the views, the smells, and the way the warm sun feels on my skin. I love the connectivity to nature and to myself. I love the pain, the sweat, the blood, the cuts and bruises. I love the challenge and all of the emotions that come along with it. I even love it when I‚Äôm uncomfortable and miserable... even if I don‚Äôt know it at the time. Like most things in life, it‚Äôs all about what you put into it, and how willing you are to give yourself over to the experience. That is where you gain and where you grow.

The sun felt warm, the shade felt cool, the air felt crisp and the wind had a bite to it. I‚Äôve never had to layer and delayer every 20 minutes so many times in my life. üòÇ But, that‚Äôs the last push of summer for you. How did you enjoy yours?

People always ask me how I balance my love for the outdoors with my love of video games. And to be honest, it‚Äôs not always easy. When I‚Äôm at home playing Skyrim, it reminds me so much of being in the mountains that it makes me wish I was out there bagging a peak. And sometimes when I‚Äôm in the mountains I look around and think ‚ÄúHoly smokes. This looks JUST like Skryim!‚Äù ‚Ä¶and then I want to go home, put on sweats and kill some dragons so I can level up my combat skills.
.
Although it can be difficult to find the balance between these two passions, I‚Äôve found that blurring the lines between the real outdoors and the virtual outdoors helps me to forget that I even need to worry about balance in the first place. Also, I‚Äôve literally never been asked that question.¬†üòÇ #thisisajoke but not really, because #skyrimislife
.

node.text: Fall is almost here. üò≥ Are you excited for it? ...or sad to see summer go?

I love a good alpine lake to cool off/freshen up in, I mean‚Ä¶ who doesn‚Äôt? Especially on a hot sunny day. Unfortunately, there usually isn‚Äôt one waiting for you back at the trailhead after a hike... but I‚Äôve found a good alternative!
.
Earlier this summer I was able to try out the plant-based skincare line from @motherdirt, and the AO+ Mist is my most loved product. It contains live AOB (Ammonia-Oxidizing Bacteria), a microorganism found in soil and critically important in nature. Similar to a probiotic, these bacteria work to enrich the skin‚Äôs natural environment. AOB consume the irritating components of our sweat and transform them into benefits for the skin, helping to restore balance, while also fighting odor causing bacteria. ‚Ä¶which is something I find very useful after I‚Äôve been sweating profusely for several hours.
.
I always pack a post-hike bag and leave it in my car for when I return from a hike or backpacking trip. And along with some clean clothes, flip flips, a wash rag and deodorant... I always throw the AO+ mist in there too now! #sponsored

I don‚Äôt catch nearly as many sunsets in the mountains as I would like. And I‚Äôm keeping my fingers crossed that I‚Äôm able to catch one or two this coming weekend - that is, if I can see through the smokey skies. üò∑
.
Wildfire season always tears at my heart strings. Knowing how much it has increased over the recent years, the evacuations, wildlife displacement, homes and lives lost, thousands and thousands of charred acres, and all of the incredible people who put their heart and soul into fighting them... it‚Äôs devastating and humbling. As smoke blankets the skies of the west coast, we are continually reminded of how delicate (and flammable) our environment really is. While most wildfires are caused naturally, please be extremely cautious when enjoying a campfire. Know how to build and put them out responsibly. AND please please please, know where you can and cannot have one and respect those rules. üôèüèº
‚ÄúIt doesn‚Äôt feel that bad once your legs go a little numb!‚Äù üòÇ
The calmest of mornings. ü§ó

Hiking and backpacking friends...
.
How prepared are you when you head out into the wilderness? Do you always have items with you to help get you through an emergency?
.
We left camp to summit a nearby peak, and I think I did pretty well. I had my @garmin InReach, an emergency bivy, a water filter, food, a couple extra layers and a small med kit. I‚Äôve been trying to be better at remembering to bring these items when I‚Äôm already deep in the mountains and about to head off trail onto more dangerous terrain. I want to be prepared in case there is an injury, whether it‚Äôs myself, my companion or a stranger I may come across.
.
But I have to admit, my day-hiking adventures could use some improvement. For whatever reason, I tend to not view them to be as risky... which is crazy considering I‚Äôve been rescued by SAR due to breaking my ankle on the trail. I tend to just think about what I might need for the 6+ hours that I‚Äôm out. But what happens if I don‚Äôt make it back? If I‚Äôm injured, or lost? ...and out there for an extra day or more?
.
I‚Äôve been thinking a lot about this over the last few days, while following the story of a missing female hiker in the North Cascades. She was last seen leaving the summit of a hike that I‚Äôve done several times, but she never made it back. My heart truly goes out to Sam Sayers and her loved ones, and I continue to hope for the best. Things like this remind me that when I head into the mountains (especially by myself), that I need to be better prepared for the unexpected. What about you? Are you as prepared as you could be when you head out? Do you always have the ten essentials and items to get you through an unexpected night or more in the wilderness? #findsamsayers

The hike in was long and thunder storms rolled in over us just in time for the final 1000‚Äô+ push up a steep cliff face. ...and the mosquitoes only got more atrocious the higher we climbed.
.
It was the kind of hike where you just want to drop your pack ASAP and fall to the ground from exhaustion, but finding a proper campsite took some time and energy. Energy neither of us really had. When we finally found a suitable place to set up camp, our first priorities were the tent (shelter from the aggressive mosquitoes) and even more desired... dinner. Except that we both failed miserably at remembering to bring one of the ten essentials - üî•. No hot meals for us. And yes coffee-lovers, that also means, no hot coffee. @justindong_ wandered off to see if there was anyone else camping in the area (spoiler alter, there wasn‚Äôt), and I stayed back and tried really hard not to cry. I was absolutely exhausted from the 10(ish) mile hike in, hangry and my patience had run dry.
.
Dehydrated meals aren‚Äôt great when they are cold, but they are perfectly edible. So we ate our meals, both impressed that we didn‚Äôt hate them as much as we expected. Day one kinda sucked to be honest. It was one of those hikes where you question what it is that you love about backpacking so much.
.
Day two was better though! Despite distant haze/smoke, the weather was lovely and the bugs seemed to have improved ever so slightly. We spent the day route-finding our way up and down two different peaks, and managed to make it back to camp before the sun completely set.
.
Day three was merely the long slog out, and boy did it feel long and miserable at times. BUT... I climbed peaks, I was surrounded by endless beauty, we had complete solitude and I was mentally, physically and maybe even emotionally challenged. And the good news is, I‚Äôll never forget matches or a lighter ever again. ü§¶üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è #youliveyoulearn #mymountaintherapy
I‚Äôm always so much more appreciative of the views I have to earn.

I just returned home from a failed backpacking trip. As we climbed higher on the trail, smoke/haze from a nearby wildfire increased and in turn decreased our visibility across the valley. We could smell the smoke, and I could feel it in my lungs and starting to irritate my eyes.
.
One member of our party was pretty adamant about wanting to turn back, while the rest of us were more inclined to push on (myself included). But at the end of the day, we weren‚Äôt exactly sure where the fire was, and therefore continuing on was potentially risky. We didn‚Äôt know, what we didn‚Äôt know... and using words like ‚Äúhopefully‚Äù and ‚Äúprobably‚Äù are never reassuring to someone who‚Äôs already uncomfortable. So with a bit of a heavy heart, we turned around with the words of my buddy rattling through our heads... ‚Äúlet‚Äôs live to hike another day.‚Äù
.
I can‚Äôt help but feel a little bummed, especially since once we got into service we discovered that we hadn‚Äôt been in danger... BUT I‚Äôve been in a situation where I was the only one who wanted to turn back and pushing forward got us in to more trouble. Trusting your gut is important in the wilderness, but everyone‚Äôs gut feelings are going to be a little different... and they all deserve respect and consideration.
.
So... we hiked out together, smiling and laughing. We got some dinner in town and found a campground for the night... only to be woken up at 3am by a dude with a chainsaw. No joke. The guy had fallen a tree earlier (most likely illegally) and he came back to cut more of it up. Thank goodness for earplugs! üò≥üôèüèº
.
The photo is from our consolation day hike on the way back home. Not a terrible day. :)

I‚Äôm finally starting to feel strong this summer! üí™üèº I‚Äôm not the best at working out on a regular basis (which is something I‚Äôd like to change). The beginning of my hiking/backpacking season is usually spent trying to get IN to hiking shape... but this weekend my pack felt lighter, I felt stronger and a trail I once thought was a little tough, wasn‚Äôt. ü§ó

Instagram vs. reality. üòÇ Swipe left to see what I‚Äôm really doing right now.
.
I was sitting at my desk at work, with my feet up... trying to think of some kind of ‚ÄúHappy Friday/Yay it‚Äôs the weekend‚Äù caption to go along with the first image. I looked at my feet on my desk and laughed as an email telling me to do my timesheets came through. Effing timesheets. üôÑüòÇ And then I thought... wouldn‚Äôt this be a funny thing to share.
.
Honestly most of my life isn‚Äôt photogenic. It‚Äôs a dimly lit office building, a messy studio apartment, a tv binge evening... I‚Äôm such a dork, I actually shed a happy tear a couple weeks ago when I found out that Elder Scrolls 6 is finally in pre-production. ...that‚Äôs a video game btw, for those who don‚Äôt know. ü§ì
.
I love hiking and backpacking. I enjoy photography and creating images. But for all of the people who want to know how to do what I do... what is that? I have a basic associate of arts degree. I work a relatively standard job as an executive assistant. I‚Äôm single with no kids (which I‚Äôm totally content with), I‚Äôm a homebody with a cat and an Xbox, who enjoys getting outside on the weekends and screwing around with a camera. And somewhere along the way I got lucky and my Instagram account began to grow... and it became my side hustle. I‚Äôm proud of what I‚Äôve created, and honored to get to work with some cool brands from time to time... but truly... my every day life is pretty darn average. And that‚Äôs not a bad thing, not at all.
.
So on that note... happy Friday/Yay it‚Äôs the weekend!!

Can you see those two guys on the rock down there?? üîé
.
I watched as they cooked and ate their dinners, while I patiently awaited for the clouds to part and the light to pour in. Even though they are so small against the giant landscape, I‚Äôm glad they were there. It‚Äôs just such a great visual representation of what I love so much about the outdoors. We come out here not only to surround ourselves with nature‚Äôs beauty, but more importantly to be a part of it - even for just a night.
.
I hope you had a great weekend! ü§ó #mymountaintherapy

Fun fact: I don‚Äôt really like water. Or perhaps a better way to say it is that I‚Äôm not super comfortable in or on the water. So when @mindbodygreen & @NatureMadeVitamins reached out to me about a campaign involving paddle boarding on a cold mountain lake, I felt... apprehensive. I‚Äôm much more comfortable with my feet on solid ground. But, I said yes to the project and about a week later I found myself on an inflatable paddle board in the middle of Lake Kachess. Being out there by myself allowed me to tune into what it is about the water that makes me so uneasy, and I think it just boils down to feeling exposed and unsure of what's below me. At one point I stopped for several minutes, observed my surroundings and the only sound I heard was that of the water around me... and I realized that I just felt really alone.
.
Even though this wasn‚Äôt some wild crazy adventure, it was still me pushing myself out of my own comfort zone. I think that‚Äôs a good takeaway here. Adventures come in all shapes and sizes and getting out of ones comfort zone doesn‚Äôt have to be something big or epic, it just requires a willingness to try and it always provides an opportunity to grow. So thank you MBG and Nature Made for the push and for helping to support my healthy lifestyle, and also BIG thank you for not putting me in the middle of the ocean instead. üò¨üôà #healthytogether #sponsored
.

I‚Äôm 5‚Äô6, 130lbs... and my swimsuit sizes range anywhere from an x-small to a large depending on the brand... and even some of the larges are a joke in terms of coverage. I adore swimwear, but man...I hate trying it on.
.
I‚Äôve read so many things lately that say the answer to being ‚Äúbikini ready‚Äù is simply just putting one on... and I don‚Äôt disagree, but damn, finding one that fits is a whole different ball game! So ladies, I ask... do you have a favorite swimwear brand that you feel is quality + true to size? It drives me nuts at how all over the map brands and their size charts are. Feeling confident in a swimsuit starts from within, but it‚Äôs sure helpful when you can find one that actually fits, covers and supports your body.

It‚Äôs been about 6 months since my second ankle surgery and many of you have sporadically asked how it‚Äôs been doing (thank you btw!). I had eight screws and a five inch metal plate removed from my right ankle towards the end of 2017, and I‚Äôm so so SO happy I made that choice. üôèüèº
.
I‚Äôm amazed at everything I was able to accomplish last year with all that metal in there, but it was a struggle - physically and mentally. It would pop and roll SO easy, ache, swell and stiffen up. Every morning I would wake up and have to limp around for several minutes until it warmed up. Heck, even if I sat down during the day and didn‚Äôt use it for 30 minutes or so, it would usually result in having to limp around for a minute to get it back up and running. ...and that was the first thing I noticed was GONE once I recovered from the removal surgery. It was like night and day.
.
My ankle still gives me a little grief here and there. It tends to ache when I run, it doesn‚Äôt like when I sit cross-legged and I have to steer clear of tall heels... but all and all it pretty much feels like a normal ankle again! The human body is incredible and although there were a few rough months... I‚Äôm actually glad it happened, because it gave me so much more appreciation for my health and my body. So for anyone who is wondering about hardware removal surgeries... I would say mine was a great success and I couldn‚Äôt recommend it high enough. I can‚Äôt wait to see the difference between this summer and last!üí™üèº
.
.
.

A few weeks back, I set out to eat healthier. You know... to get a jump on the holiday over-indulgence. Naturally I went to the grocery store and stocked up on food that was "good" for me. And then I watched a few documentaries on diet, health, animal agriculture and the environment... and they CHANGED my life.
.
My desire to drop a few pounds morphed into adopting a whole-foods plant based diet, and to begin pursuing a vegan lifestyle - something I'd been thinking about for a couple years. And aside from some jokes and judgement, it's been surprisingly easier than I thought it would be.
.
I feel better, I'm sleeping better, food tastes better, I have more energy... which are all great things... but more importantly, I'm eating with intention. And with every meal I feel better about not contributing to the industries that are harming our health, our planet and our animals. I can honestly say, I believe it is the best decision I've ever made... I only wish I'd made it sooner.
.
For those interested, What the Health and Cowspiracy were two of the many documentaries that I found to be impactful. As with everything, take the information with a grain of salt and keep doing your research.
.
.
.

I remember the moment I decided I wanted to become a hiker. It was a pleasantly warm spring day and I was at the park, laying in the sun. I was newly single... and sad. Sad that I was back to "square one," but also that I'd lost this person to go do things with. I know I've talked about this many times in previous posts, but it will never cease to amaze me at how that one tiny (and yet huge) revelation, that if I wanted to go do something, I could do it on my own, has changed my life.
.
It's changed the way I see myself and given me a sense of independence and purpose, it has changed my social circle and altered how I view relationships and being on my own... and of course it's brought me to a place where I'm able to tell so many of you all about something so small, and yet so meaningful to me.
.
Can you remember the exact moment your life changed course?
.
.

One of my favorite trips over the summer was when I set out for four days by myself. It was beautiful, therapeutic, rewarding, and it was an accomplishment for me. It was my first solo multi-night adventure.
.
I didn't grow up in the mountains. I actually didn't even consider myself to be "outdoorsy" until about 5 or 6 years ago, and it's taken time and experience to gain the confidence I needed to head out on solo trips. Day hikes were easy, but the overnight... it took me a while before I felt brave enough to go. But I'm so glad I did, because those are the trips that bring an even deeper connection to nature.
.
We all have to start somewhere and we all start as beginners. I personally don't feel like I'm doing anything extraordinary, but I take pride in my outdoor accomplishments... however small, large or common they might be.
.

There it is again, that funny little yellow mat that I almost always have in my 'out-the-tent-door' photos. Anytime I post a photo like this, I get questions about it. So what it is? It's just the bottom portion of a Therm-a-Rest Z-Pad. I cut a section of my full length (and too long for me) pad off, in order to create a sit pad that I could take out with me. They do sell actual sit pads, but I opted against spending more money. ...but this little sit pad actually gets used far more as a 'welcome mat' than anything else. It's become one of my backpacking staples. It's a simple thing, but I love having a place to put my bare feet or socks on when taking off or putting on my hiking boots. Obviously it still works great as a sit pad. It also works well if you need to stand up outside to change your pants. It's basic things like this that make my backpacking experiences that much more enjoyable. What's one of yours?
.
.

STORY TIME!! Last week I walked down to the basement garage of my apartment building, and I noticed my drivers side door slightly ajar. As I got closer I noticed something large in the front seat. My heart was racing, as my first thought was that it was a person. Another slow step or two debunked that idea. I opened my door and there it was... a red tote bag, and inside of that was a large plastic bag, tied at the top... with something inside. I took the bag out of my car and stared at it. There was no name. No address. No note. I ripped the plastic open, only to find an overnight backpack & some trekking poles, which I had been expecting. But what were these items (that should have arrived in a box and been delivered to the lobby or my door) doing in my car?
.
I returned to my car and found my things had been rifled through. Everything in the glove box & console had been strewn all over the floor and passenger seat, and the small amount of cash I kept was gone. I'd been robbed, and oddly gifted my own items all at the same time, which is kinda funny... until you consider that the person who got in, must have known the car was mine.
.
When I was 20 years old I had a stalker. A complete stranger watched me where I worked and most likely followed me home several times. My sixth sense had been going haywire for 2-3 weeks prior to him making himself known (which is another story), but the experience was terrifying. So when the above happened... I couldn't help but be fearful that someone was targeting me specifically, again.
.
The good news is, security footage shows that the culprit tried about 7 other cars (with the bag in hand) before reaching my car... which embarrassingly was left unlocked. Another car pulled into the garage, he left the bag inside, hid for several minutes and then walked away, leaving the items in my car. So, apparently it was all just a strange coincidence... ü§î
.
Although this story ends with me just being a victim of a weird/common crime, I couldn't help but be reminded of an experience that taught me that there are some bad people out there and that we're more vulnerable than we realize. But also, to just lock my damn door.

What would I do without you?
.
.
.
.

I remember one of the early ‚Äúbusiness‚Äù offers I got here on Instagram. A solar backpack company contacted me about doing a post for them. Their original offer was for product + an unspecified amount of compensation, in exchange for a post on my Instagram page. I responded, gave them my measly rate and got their response ‚Äúsorry‚Ä¶ we only pay influencers who have over 50k followers‚Äù (I had roughly 35k) - so I declined. Sure maybe I could have accepted the backpack (something I didn‚Äôt need or want) and sold it afterwards, but I said no on principal. Even to this day, I get these same kind of offers. And then others like this: "We'd love to gift one of our products! All we ask is that you take a photo and tag us!‚Äù Oh yay, a gift with strings attached! 100% no.
.
I‚Äôm sure a fair amount of you have received similar offers, and perhaps you were stoked at the idea of free sh!t. I get it. And hey, when it‚Äôs something you really do want or need, perhaps the value of your time, work and then advertising to your followers is worth it. Perhaps it‚Äôs not. That‚Äôs entirely up to you, but it‚Äôs important to realize that many brands are fishing for cheap/free work, exposure and advertising. And worse, a lot of us are saying yes.
.
Social media marketing is here, it‚Äôs growing, it‚Äôs effective and brands are greatly expanding their budgets. And while it might be fun to receive free things and get to 'work' with brands, at the end of the day you‚Äôre undervaluing yourself, and brands are stoked about it.
.
If you don't value your work or your time... who will?
.
.
.

I'm sure many of you have noticed that I don't tag locations in my posts anymore. I used to offer general locations, but have since stopped. I've explained many times in comments when people inquire, but I've never written an actual post about it.
.
My not tagging locations doesn't come from a desire to keep it a secret from you and it doesn't stem from an elitist mindset (as I've been accused of). I don't tag locations because I feel that with a following of my size, it would be irresponsible of me to blast the locations of these fragile and sometimes pretty remote areas to literally thousands of people. The amount of likes a photo gets is a mere fraction compared to how many people actually view it.
.
I know I'll continue to get nasty comments and direct messages from time to time, but that's ok. There's an incredible amount of information already out there on the internet, in guide books, and plenty of other people posting locations. I don't feel the need to add to it, especially when I see so many places being overrun and abused. I just want to inspire people to get out in nature in a general sense, and to share my stories. Perhaps some of you don't agree with the way I go about things, but I do hope you'll respect how I run my page... and thank you to those of you who already support me. üôèüèº
.
.
.

I spent three nights in the mountains by myself, and it was incredible. It was actually my first solo multi-night trip, and (sorry Dad) it certainly won't be my last. I'll admit, even with as much as I enjoy backpacking, I started the hike in some pretty intense winds and was questioning why I was out there... and my heavy pack indicated that I'd brought too much stuff. That night the winds picked up even more and my tent was collapsing on top of me. It was hard to not be alarmed at first, ...but I put my ear plugs in, turned my back to the wind and eventually fell back to sleep.
.
The next morning while I was eating breakfast I saw another solo woman cruise by (wearing a dress no less). I watched her stop up ahead and take a break. She dropped her pack, took her sweaty hair down and shook it out, drank some water, ate a snack, took a few pictures and continued on a few minutes later. I never spoke with her, but she was awesome. And I want that dress.
.
Long story short, she reminded me why I was there. Because I can be, because I want to be and because there's nothing quite like it. So I packed up and headed deeper into the mountains and proceeded to have the most amazing time.
.
.

Tonight I'd like to talk about sponsored posts. It's kind of one of those things that we're all aware of, but we don't talk much about. Instead we just try to sneak them in here and there...sometimes blatantly, sometimes not so blatantly. It's something that I struggle with, because one part of me is so effing stoked that I've been able to monetize my account, and another part of me dislikes it because I know you didn't follow me to see ads.
.
I remember a few years ago... pre-"instafame" when one of my co-workers said "it's too bad you can't turn your hiking hobby into a job!" At that time I was just a receptionist at a marketing agency, living paycheck to paycheck and putting far too much on credit cards. I often thought about getting a second job. Maybe I'd work as a barista or a bartender in the evenings and on weekends... but my heart hurt every time I realized I'd have to give up my free time in the mountains or with family and friends in order to live more comfortably and pay the bills.
.
I didn't start my IG page with the intention of monetizing it, but eventually my account grew large enough and I saw an opportunity. So I focused, I strategized and I turned my love for the outdoors and photography into a paying job. It definitely has its pros and cons, but ultimately I'm super grateful and proud of what I've built. I still have a regular job and I fully intend on keeping it. I like the balance and honestly I think social media is too unstable to put my all my eggs all in one basket. But now, I'm able to save money and pay off debt, and as much I know sponsored posts bother some of you, I have to do what's right for me. So I hope you can all understand and respect that, but I also hope you know that I'm not just here to make money. I get the most enjoyment out of the conversations that take place, the community aspect and when someone tells me that I've inspired them... even in the tiniest of ways. That's what motivates me to keep at this and I hope that's what shines through the most.
.
.
.

Quick Story: Two years ago I did an easy group hike in the morning and then headed out for a solo backpacking trip in the afternoon, all in 90+ degree heat. My sister deleted her Instagram account today. She was tired of Instagram determining what she should see and in what order. She got rid of Facebook several months ago too. It seems like such a silly thing to care about, but I get it. I find it very frustrating as well. Every time I post now I wonder if I'll get "algorithmed" - which can either be a good thing or a bad thing. Either my post will be deemed as something you all should see, or it won't. I receive emails from companies about purchasing followers and engagement a few times a month. Users are being banned from hashtags. Comment pods are popping up all over the place. ...for those who don't know what they are, it's a group of users all in the same DM string, and every time someone posts something new, they send a message to the group and everyone else likes and comments on it. It's supposed to help engagement by way of tricking the algorithm into seeing your post as "quality." Does it work? Maybe. I tried one out a while back for all of about a week before I left it. It felt crappy. I don't want anyones support or praise unless they actually want to offer it all on their own.
.
Social media feeling like a popularity contest isn't anything new, but I do think it's gotten uglier over time. I try to not let it bother me, but it does sometimes. I've watched my engagement drop and growth slow, but at the end of the day it doesn't change anything about who I am or what I love to do. Which is why I hope you follow along. I love being in nature and I love taking photos. I've loved both longer than I've been @missholldoll. And even when my Instagram days are over, I can promise that you'll still find me out in the mountains... taking a whole lotta photos.
.
I'm curious how the IG experience has changed for any of you. Do you notice it? Do you care? Sorry for the novel. üò¨
.

Well Iceland... you've been amazing, but this hike was easily one of the highlights of the trip. @chelseakauai and I met @joe_shutter and @frankframesthings on our third day, by chance, while finishing up lunch and we got to chatting... and a couple days later, we met up again and they took us out to this incredibly special place.
.
This trip was wonderful because we never really had a set agenda. Sure, we had an idea of some of the places we wanted to go and the things we wanted to see, but the best memories weren't created at those iconic Icelandic viewpoints that everyone has seen a thousand times. They happened when we chose to be spontaneous. I saw such a tiny fraction of what Iceland had to offer, but I definitely experienced enough to know that I want to come back and experience so much more.
.

Havasupai was more beautiful and special than I expected it to be. And part of what made it special was hiking in on my own two feet, and truly earning it (even with a recovering ankle). **For those who don't want to hike, there is a helicopter option worth looking into. There are also pack horses, but I would HIGHLY recommend doing your research on how those animals are treated before making that choice. I saw many that appeared malnourished and there are a lot of stories of abuse out there. While I can't personally attest to those, I think it's important to do your research and know what you're supporting before you go. .
.

The ranger told us that if rain was coming we would know it. He said it would get dark and the winds would kick up suddenly... and he was right. A few minutes after this photo was taken the temperature dropped, dark clouds rolled in and the winds kicked up in what felt like an instant. There was so much mist swirling around us that it was hard to tell if it had even started raining yet or not. It was about all we could do to climb up from Mooney Falls as fast as we possibly could. It's those moments that stick with me the most... shivering, climbing up the muddy ladder rungs and chains set in place on the rock wall, and telling myself to just keep moving. Thankfully it's a relatively short climb and we made it to the top. ...but those "Get me the F outta here" moments are always some of the most memorable!

For anyone that's read my old blog posts, you might remember the first one I ever wrote, which explains where my love for hiking came from. That entire story feels a little lengthy for tonight's caption, but I will tell you that it was something I discovered on my own. I spent many years feeling like there were so many things I didn't want to do... or couldn't do by myself (which is a real tragedy), and hiking was one of them. I didn't really have outdoorsy friends at that time in my life, so I started hitting the local trails solo - almost forcing myself to learn to like it. It felt strange at first, but then it felt therapeutic. Not too long after, I sought out longer, more scenic hikes and venturing further away from home. The more I got out and explored, the more I wanted to see. I became addicted, in the best way. I couldn't believe I'd grown up in such an amazing place and not even really known it. Slowly I gained outdoor friends and integrated backpacking into the mix. Also something I never thought I would do alone, until I did... and I loved it. I also thought I'd never summit a peak by myself, until I did. Here's a shot from one of my favorite backpacking trips to date. One I did by myself and I took this shot on the way down from Del Campo Peak. I made it back to camp a little while later, packed up my stuff and hiked out - reaching my car just before the sun set and grinning ear to ear. So here's to trying new things - you never know where it might lead.

Hi guys! üëãüèº It's been a while since I've introduced myself, but I think now is a decent time to catch some people up. My name is Holly, I'm in my 30's and I live in the beautiful and sometimes dreary city of Seattle. It's probably relatively obvious that I enjoy hiking, backpacking, fair weather and playing around with a camera. What you may not know about me is that I work full-time at an advertising agency and I live with my hilarious cat-child roommate. I don't have a favorite anything I don't think, but instead, multiple favorites that usually shift over time. My tastes change constantly and I prefer to adapt to those. On a personal note, I'm single (obviously... I have a cat üíÅüèΩ) and I live by my own personal motto of "I'd rather find the right guy in ten years than the wrong guy tomorrow" - so I don't really date much. I think too much time and energy is spent on trying to find someone to fit into our lives, that sometimes we forget to just live for ourselves. ü§∑üèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è Most of you know that I broke my ankle out hiking just before Christmas, had surgery two weeks later and spent many of the following weeks recovering. It was a challenging, humbling and also inspiring time in my life. Three months after surgery, I was backpacking again and I even went rock climbing last weekend. üôåüèº I'm not fully recovered, and honestly I may never be 100%, but that's ok and it's a great reminder that accidents can happen and change your life (temporarily or permanently) in an instant. I think I'll stop there, but hopefully you learned something new about me that you didn't know before. Assuming you read all that babble of course. üòú‚úåüèº PC: @goldiehawn_

Yet another article has come out pitting outdoor women against outdoor women on social media. üòî The author writes: "These women look nothing like I do when I‚Äôm playing outside. I‚Äôm usually dirty and sweaty, with hair flying out of my ponytail (unattractively, not whimsically, for the record), or bundled up in functional gear that keeps me from freezing to death. So are my female adventure buddies, for that matter." - I think that passage alone shows the true colors of the author and the message relayed by @misadventuresmg.
.
After recently returning from a four day backpacking trip with three other women, all with relatively large followings on social media, I'm not entirely sure what to think. We all got sweaty, dirty, stinky and wore functional clothing and gear... and yet articles like these point the finger in a way that makes me feel like our authenticity is somehow in question because of the kind of photos we came back with. 
To outdoor women everywhere. You are awesome and you are beautiful. Whether you choose to post pictures of the dirt under your fingernails, or yourself standing in front of the beautiful landscape you worked so hard to get to (whilst unleashing your gorgeous dirty sweaty hair), you are inspiring. For as inclusive as this community can feel, I'm astonished at how exclusive it really can be sometimes. 
Regardless, I can't wait to get out hiking and backpacking, bag some peaks and take the kind of photos that I like to take. And I'll keep brushing my hair... because if I don't, that sweaty dirty mess will literally turn into a rats nest... and I ain't got time for that. üòÇ Ladies, wear what you want, do your hair how you want, post what you want - at the end of the day I just hope you'll be safe, do your research and practice good outdoor ethics. Thanks for posting about this @missmeghanyoung - I can't wait to see your smiling face in the backcountry, lipstick and all. üì∑: @jayboyzee

I didn't walk on this trail today, but six weeks after ankle surgery, I walked (unassisted) into my post-op appointment. üôåüèº The x-ray tech was floored by how well everything looked. He said I looked more like 12 weeks post-op, not six... and I had the biggest grin on my face. ‚ò∫ Although my full range of motion isn't back yet, and I will continue to deal with swelling and stiffness, my surgeon has lifted all restrictions on what I am allowed to do. Now, I just have listen to my body, test the waters and "fake it till I make it" - his words. I think the best part of all of this was discovering just how strong I really am.
Happy ‚ù§Ô∏è day everyone!! Xoxo
Miss you.

I remember laying in bed one night with my broken ankle propped up, trying to fall asleep... but I was so uncomfortable and my mind was racing. So I searched on my phone for any information I could find about my upcoming surgery and recovery. I ended up in one of many online forums where people wrote about their broken ankle experience... the pain, the swelling, the medication and the side-effects, the medication FOR the side-effects, the number of plates and screws... the crutches, the boots, the limping... the can and can'ts, shoulds and shouldn'ts, the lengthy and varying timelines and stages, the depression... and I cried. But it was after I cried that I became determined. I was going to heal and I was going to heal as quickly as humanly possible. As much as I want to be out there in the mountains, in all honesty... it wasn't about that. It was just about making a deal with my mind and my body that I was going do everything I could possibly do to help myself. Because just succumbing to the situation and the average timeframe of all the various stages in recovery wasn't going to be my story. .
.
I have my six week post-op appointment on Wednesday next week, and guess who will be confidently walking in... on her very own two feet? üôãüèΩ I will. .
.
üì∑: @jayboyzee

I don't deny that snow makes everything look incredibly beautiful and it's pretty darn fun at times.... but at the end of the day, I thrive so much more in the warmer months.

Even though I can‚Äôt hike right now, getting back to the mountains is a HUGE part of what motivates me to recover. I want 2017 to be the start of the healthiest version of me and I don't have time to be sick. Thankfully, #Theraflu gets me through the cold and flu season, so that I can get back to important things ‚Ä¶ cuz I‚Äôve got some peaks to bag this summer!! What do you not want to miss out on? Thank you everyone for hanging in there while I continually post old photos from before my ankle injury. I wondered at first if I would continue to post during this time, but I'm glad I've kept at it. It's helped me feel connected, supported and even more excited about my recovery. ‚ò∫

Do you remember the moment you fell in love with the outdoors? It didn't happen for me immediately, in fact... I remember the first hike I went on before I "got into" hiking. I hadn't been on a hike since I was a kid, I wasn't in shape, it was all uphill and in the forest... and when I made it to the top and saw little to no views I audibly said "this is it???" üòè I didn't fall in love with the outdoors then, but it was that hike that propelled me to get physically fit and to get a better attitude. I fell in love with the outdoors shortly after, along with the new me.

To say that I'm looking forward to warm sunny mornings in the mountains would be a pretty big understatement. That and breakfast burritos. üåØ Those two just go hand in hand for me! What's your go-to mountain breakfast?

Guess who gets to start taking her first steps next week?? THIS GIRL! üôåüèº For those of you who don't know, I broke my ankle six weeks ago and I had surgery four weeks ago. I now have one metal plate and eight screws holding everything together and helping my bones to heal properly. I've got a ways to go, but I'm gonna get there! And once I'm back... I've got some trails to hit, some peaks to bag... and maybe I'll vacation in Hawaii or something. ü§îüå¥üå§
I don't like waking up early... unless it's for this. üíú

Taking a break on the TMB. This picture brings back memories of a tough day of hiking and racing an incoming weather system. It was day seven and my body and my mind were exhausted, but man... what an incredible trip. Anyone thinking of hiking the Tour du Mont Blanc this year? üì∑: @jayboyzee

Some places really are... for lack of better words... magical. ‚ú® I'm thinking about the things I want to do once I'm back on my own two feet, and a trip down the Oregon coast sounds prettty nice! ü§ó

I may be down right now, but I'm not out. I had my first physical therapy appointment yesterday and although we couldn't do much, it was still exciting for me. I know it's important to be patient... but it's also important to celebrate every single day that my ankle gets even the tiniest bit stronger. I'm very thankful to have doctors that want me to get back on the trail just as much as I do. ‚ò∫ PC: @thejessiemorris
I'm missing these views so much right now. üò≠ I'm pretty sure they're missing me too though. ;)

It only took nearly a year and one broken ankle, but I've finally got a NEW BLOG POST up on My Mountain Therapy! Spoiler alert, it's about my broken ankle and the story of how it happened. Check it out if you want! The link is in my bio.

Focus on the things you can control and let go of what you can't... that's what I keep telling myself. After having a mini meltdown this evening, I reminded myself to just focus on what I can control. I can't do anything about the fact that I have a broken ankle and that it's going to heal in it's own damn time, but I can still focus on being as healthy as I can be... so I ate a delicious salad and then I did some exercises on the floor. It's a win for tonight. Next up, tomorrow! üì∑: @jayboyzee

Daydreaming of travel. I was supposed to be leaving for Belize in a few days, but... rappelling down a waterfall with a broken ankle just sounded like a bad idea. üòú Combing through old photos and thinking about future trips helps though. :) Where's your next trip?

Several weeks ago I posted about how I felt change coming and some kind of reinvention of myself. I didn't know what that would look like, and I still don't... but I know I was correct and that I'm going through it right now. I think injury can do that to/for a person, depending on how it's internalized. Wishing everyone a wonderful 2017... I may not be starting out on the right foot (haha get it?) but I have a really great feeling about this year! ‚ò∫

Well guys, my ankle surgery is scheduled for Tuesday of next week. I'll get some hardware in there and begin the process of recovery. I can't say I'm excited for the surgery itself, but I'm definitely excited to be one step closer to walking again! üì∑: @jayboyzee

Six months ago I hiked 110 miles on the Tour du Mont Blanc trek, and now... I can't even walk to the bathroom. üòÇ Things can change in an instant. Broken ankle and all, I'm doing well and in good spirits. Things could be so much worse, and I'm determined to have a speedy and complete recovery. In the interim, I still have a ton of photos I can post from previous adventures... so even though I'm not actually "out there" right now, I'm not gone. :) Thank you to all the folks that have commented and messaged me - I really appreciate all the kind words and support! You're the best! And big thanks to my sis @hdavis2220 for taking care of me these last few days. üì∑: @jayboyzee

Two nights ago I ran up Rattlesnake Ledge to catch sunset, and it was beautiful. But shortly after this photo was taken I had an accident. On the way down, only minutes from the top, I hit a patch of ice, slipped, tried to recover and rolled my ankle to the point of breaking it in two places. I'd heard a horrible crack and hoped it was a stick, but it wasn't. I tried to get up, but my ankle and foot were just... floppy, and it kept giving out. The moment you realize you're really injured is kinda sickening. 
Lucky for me, two hikers were only minutes behind me and immediately jumped in to help. @hawaiian_grl_pnw took my pack and headed down the trail to seek assistance and @a.pnw.rose stayed with me, and helped me hobble down (about 3/4 of a mile), to where we finally got cell service. Once we discovered that Search and Rescue were on the way, we took a seat and waited. An entire crew of SAR volunteers came out just after 7pm to get me down the trail safely. It was incredible and humbling to see and I'm so very thankful for all the kindness I received. @a.pnw.rose even helped me get home and coordinated getting my car back to my apartment. Oh and she's picking me up and taking me to my sisters for Christmas Eve tomorrow. I am truly blessed. 
Anything can happen to anyone at any time. I consider Rattlesnake to be a piece of cake, but simple accidents can happen anywhere. Be as prepared as you can be - I could have been more so.  @eddiebauer #liveyouradventure #ebcontributor

node.text: Classic PNW moment.
Oh the Cascades... they sure are easy on the eyes! üòç And now they are all covered in snow!! I can't wait to see the difference this coming weekend.

At home when the weather forecast looks like garbage, I opt inside... but sometimes you don't have a choice. The temperature and weather conditions varied quite a bit towards the end of our 10 day Tour du Mont Blanc trek, and temps had dropped significantly on our last three days. We went from 70-80+ degrees to 30-40's degrees and eventually snowing.... in July. üò≥ PC: @jayboyzee

I found $18 out hiking yesterday. While picking up the money I thought "hmmm, I bet I'll end up losing something while I'm out today." I tend to believe in the balance of things... you win some, you lose some. You find $18 cash, you drop a glove. Well I didn't drop a glove. My camera and tripod fell down a cliff/ledge a good 30-35'. After downclimbing in the snow and ice, and losing feeling in both hands... I was able to retrieve my items and climb back up. Amazingly, the camera works, but my wide angle lens is damaged. ...and apparently my fingers are too, as they are still partially numb. BUT guess who found $18 on the trail yesterday!!??? üôãüèΩ I did.

Washington is about to get slapped with its first storm(s) of the season. Lots of wind, rain and snow in the mountains. So here's a picture from a much drier time in my life. Hold on to your hats and ponytails fellow Washingtonians! üì∑ helper: @roundtheworldgirl üòò

Oh summer. I'm really gonna miss you üò¢ ::sigh:: So to answer a few more questions from my post a couple days ago. 1) Am I going to ever revisit/add to my blog again? Ugh. I want to. Sadly, I feel like I hit a writers block over a year ago, and I lost my motivation. I just haven't felt the drive or desire to write again, which kinda bums me out. I am hoping to reconnect with writing again, because I really did love that outlet for a period of time, and building my website was really fun! 2) @roundtheworldgirl keeps asking if I have a solar powered curling iron that I take with me. Yes. Yes, I do. üòÇ just kidding. Alright, to put the hair questions to rest... the simple and boring truth is, I'm not a sweaty mess when I hike. It's not that I don't hike hard or push myself, I just don't ever get that sweaty! My sister can even vouch for me. Even after many miles, I can take my hair down and it usually looks and smells pretty ok. For example... I recently went backpacking, came back and went to work two days in a row with my dirty mountain hair. I know, gross. What can I say? I'm just really lazy. I do take a travel hairbrush with me when I backpack though - tangles are no joke. 3) How do I fund my travels and is Instagram my sole form of income? No. I work a full time job as an Executive Assistant at an advertising agency, and I just use my weekends and time off to the best of my ability. My "regular" job is my main source of income. Instagram/social media projects are secondary. So that's it! On a totally unrelated note... who's watched Westworld on HBO? I'm pretty excited about this. ü§ì

Waking up for sunrise wasn't easy yesterday. It was dark and it was cold, but I could see a dusting of snow on the tops of the peaks and I instantly felt like a little kid that wanted to go play in it. So I threw on my boots, layered up and attempted to race the sun. ...it felt like I won anyway. ;) @muckbootco #muckboots #partner

How often do you catch yourself saying something like "I can't believe how fast this year has gone?" or "I can't believe how quickly summer flew by" or in my case right now... I can't believe it's October! üò≥üéÉ At any rate, all those little sayings really do is remind me how short this life really is. Time will pass, it will fly right by us... and we don't have a say in that. But, we do have a say in how we spend that time and who we spend it with. Choose wisely.

The best part of my day was this view. I mean, obviously. But the second best part of my day was when I accidentally put my new @camelbak Chute water bottle to the test. While scrambling down from the summit, the bottle fell out of my side pouch and bounced off boulders some 30-40' down... and this was my expression: üò≥ But when I got down to it, aside from a couple small scratches, it was miraculously unharmed! Which is what I need in my life. I need an indestructible, vacuum insulated, leak-proof water bottle. ...and mountain views.... and beef jerky.... and gummy bears. #gotyourbak #sponsored
Such a tease...

I missed Bagel Monday at work to have breakfast in the mountains with my sister. This was our first backpacking trip together in over 20 years! üò≥ Definitely worth the vacation day and missing out on an a delicious asiago bagel.

On the way down from the summit, @jayboyzee and I spied this scene. He asked me if I thought I could get up on that rock in the distance... I looked at him said "...there's only one way to find out" and started running down the trail. #teamwork üì∑: @jayboyzee
I've got a yearning to go climb up something.

When I reflect on my summer, it felt short. I think they always do to an extent, but here in Washington summer got started late and fall came early. I still got out on a decent amount of adventures... but, the one that brings the biggest grin to my face was the solo trip I took just a few weeks ago. It was everything I needed it to be and everything I'd forgotten that I needed. I can't say I prefer to go backpacking by myself, but I've found that time alone in the backcountry has become a necessity every once in a while, and it's important for me to carve that time out intentionally.
If I could just order this scene up with my morning coffee that would be great. Something tells me I'll have to settle for coffee and a cinnamon Danish on the way to work though. üòè
Don't get so focused on what's in the distance, that you forget to see the beauty right in front of you.

I had zero intentions of going hiking this weekend. I also had zero intentions of @jayboyzee and I getting a flat tire at 11pm at night on a forest service road... but things don't always go as planned. Am I right, or am I right? üì∑: @jayboyzee

Today won't look like this for me. I'm currently laying in bed, one cat is staring at me... the other is pacing and meowing because she wants breakfast. It's dreary and gray outside. ...I'm thinking I'll go get coffee, go to the gym.. get brunch with my bestie (not sure in what order) and then I'll clean up the nightmare pile of accumulated stuff from the last two weekends. There's something lovely about days like this though, right? They are rejuvenating in their own way... but I don't think it will keep me from daydreaming about this spot. ::sigh:: Happy Saturday everyone! üì∑: @aarongerski

Pretty pictures are lovely, but at the end of the day, that's usually all they are. On this day, I set my tripod up and ran around taking a few "pretty pictures" to capture the experience, but it tells you nothing about the day itself. I ventured out alone, drove several hours, hiked over 8 miles and gained over 5000' of elevation. I felt happy, fit, free, independent, accomplished... but I also recall feeling a little lonely at times. It was a great day though, just me, the trail and my thoughts... but for you, all I have is this "pretty" picture.
I love how changing my perspective, even just a little, opens up so many new paths and possibilities. Don't you?
It really is just about the simple things in life. Simple, quiet, perfect moments like this. üì∑: @intothinair

What gets you through the work week? For me it's a combination of memories from the previous weekend, evenings catching up with friends and the anticipation for the next adventure. ...and coffee. A fair amount of coffee. üòú

I headed into the beautiful North Cascades on Friday for a solo backpacking trip, and I summited my first peak by myself! üôåüèΩ It felt great to be entirely on my own schedule and to forget about everything... even the time of day. I lingered most of the day on Saturday and returned to my car just before sunset. As I rolled into Seattle... seeing all the people ready to go out, and tons of girls in dresses and heels walking around, I chuckled... that used to be me. üç∏üë† üôà Now, the weekend isn't complete unless I return home with salty skin, dirt under my nails and a few new scrapes and bruises. My my, how things change... ‚ò∫Ô∏è
This weekend took some unexpected turns. Plans seemed to change almost hourly... but that's ok. It always works out in the end.
I think blowing up my sleeping pad is probably my least favorite part of setting up camp... but I sure love it when my little nest is ready to jump in to!
Time in the mountains is always time well spent. Always.

The one major difference between hiking the Tour du Mont Blanc and hiking here in Washington were the alpine lakes. Or lack there of. We didn't see many and if we did, they were usually pretty far off in the distance.  I didn't realize how much I would miss them... but thankfully they were here waiting for me when I returned. üòâ Photo by: @jayboyzee

I've had a pretty great summer, but last weekend was one of my favorites. Lots of miles, hot temps, annoying bugs, water so cold it made me whimper.... wonderful company, tons of laughs, amazing views, a hilarious dog... and not surprising, I returned from it all feeling renewed and happy. Thank you for a fantastic weekend @aarongerski @sam__davis @mrs_jen_davis_ and the one and only @dieseltheadventuredog ...aka the love of my life.

All I know is that I've got a LOT more to see in this world. Like a lot, a lot. 
I had dinner with a friend last night, and even when discussing my home state of Washington, we realized how we've only scratched the surface of some areas.
Goodnight Moon üåô
Note to self: remember to pack a helmet the next time @aarongerski comes to town.

I remember a time when I felt pretty unhappy with life, and I didn't know why or what was missing. I recall thinking things like "next year will be better," but even then... I didn't know what "better" really looked like. Well, it dawned on me recently that I haven't thought like that in quite a while, and I think the difference now is that I stopped waiting for life to happen the way I thought it was supposed to... and I just started living instead. üì∑: @jayboyzee

Sometimes it's easy to get off track. To focus on the little things, the wrong things. I'm often surprised to see how petty we can be as humans, and what it is we waste our time, our energy and our breath on. Who we waste it on. ...but nothing is wasteful if we learn something, right? I think it's good to check-in with ourselves every once in while and figure out if we are really on track to whatever is important to us, and shift our course if necessary. For me, it's making sure I'm living for myself and not someone else, not comparing myself to or judging others, along with being a good, thankful, humble and kind person... not just publicly, but all the time. ...But I digress. These are just my thoughts tonight and I felt like sharing them. Anyway, here's another shot of me in the mountains... my absolute favorite place for self-reflection. üì∑: @jordanvoth

After just a few sessions at an indoor climbing gym, I put my new skills to the test at Smith Rock. Here I am on a 5.9 climb and I was excited, nervous, scared and proud all at the same time. At one point though, fear kicked in a little more strongly than I would have liked and I felt a little stuck. It didn't last long, I worked through the problem and made it to the top... but in that time where I was stuck I realized being afraid served zero purpose. Go up or go down, but don't just sit there. In life, your career, love and relationships, rock climbing... whatever it is, fear is a useless emotion and gets you nowhere. üì∑: @jayboyzee

Hey everyone! I want to thank each of you who took the time to comment on my post yesterday. I didn't have the time to comment back to everyone, but I read each and every comment. What a conversation it sparked! I'm so thrilled and yet horribly saddened by the amount of people that said they are also having to pack out garbage. Social media sites, like this one, are undoubtedly responsible for the increased foot traffic to many beautiful areas worldwide. So let's use Instagram to get the message out that we have to protect these scared places. If you are interested in the outdoors, please visit the link in my profile for some really useful information, and please show some respect to our amazing lands and to the people around you. PC: @hdavis2220

Ahhh beautiful Blanca Lake. A popular Washington hike. That teal water attracts people from all over. It's beauty amazes me every time. What also amazed me on the hike out was how much garbage was left at the viewpoint - the area where most people stop to take the classic lake photo and enjoy a bite to eat. We stopped there briefly on the way out and I noticed a ton of garbage strewn about and stuffed under rocks. I collected an ENTIRE plastic grocery bag full of trash (the a-holes left one behind). There were bottles, take out boxes, plastic wrap, food scraps, etc. I was livid. I packed it up and @mrooklyn packed it out. 
The amount of people on the trails has greatly increased over the last couple years and I can only imagine that Instagram has played a part in that. I think it's wonderful that so many people are inspired to get outside and explore beautiful places like this, but it's sad at the lack of respect that exists. Pack it in, and pack it out. It's not hard. My other friends that happened to be at the lake overnight also picked up trash along the way and witnessed some people cutting tree limbs to make room for a tent in an area that clearly wasn't a designated camp site. It's disheartening and it makes me incredibly sad. If you can't respect the outdoors, then stay inside where you belong.

Taking a queue from my sister @hdavis2220 I think I'll post some of my favorite moments from 2014 over the next few days. This past summer I tackled my first solo backpack trip and it was liberating to say the least. Truth be told, I turned around at one point - heading back to the car. It was totally fogged in, raining and cold, couldn't see a thing... and after a few miles I stopped dead on the trail for a solid 15-20 minutes and debated with myself on continuing further. I thought this wasn't what I wanted my first solo backpack experience to be, so I started heading back down to the car. Three minutes later I stopped again and turned right back around and headed for the top. I was wet and cold, couldn't see much... but it was the best decision I could have made. I seriously cannot wait for more solo trips this summer!
